  "notes": "Abkhaz (аԥсшәа) — Northwest Caucasian, written since 1954 in an extended Cyrillic alphabet. INPUT CONTRACT: Cyrillic text in the modern (1954) Abkhaz orthography, Unicode NFC, lowercase folding applied by the engine. The orthography is heavily DIGRAPHIC: the modifier letters ⟨ь⟩ (palatalisation) and ⟨ә⟩ U+04D9 (labialisation) combine with a base consonant to spell a distinct phoneme (гь /ɡʲ/, гә /ɡʷ/, шь /ʃ/, шә /ʃʷ/, ҟә /qʷʼ/ …), so every such digraph is listed as its own grapheme key and is matched by maximal munch ahead of the bare letter. Only two vowels are phonemic, /ɑ/ and /ɨ/; ⟨е о и у⟩ historically represent /ɑj ɑw jɨ wɨ/ sequences and are mapped to their surface values /e o i(j) u(w)/ as given in the alphabet table. ⟨ь⟩ and ⟨ә⟩ never occur alone as phonemes and are therefore not given standalone entries.",
